name: Ivory Bracelet
hint: Bracelets were worn by both men and women, rich and poor. They could be made of bone, ivory, metal, or polished stone.

objdescr_s: green glaze eye amulet, large. New Empire
name: Eye (Wadjet) Amulet
hint:
A powerful symbol of protection, the eye was sometimes a symbol of the goddess Wadjet; but it could also represent the "Eye of Horus" or the "Eye of Ra."

Part of the challenge of studying Egypt is symbols can have multiple meanings. Gods and goddesses can have many different, and even contradictory, traits!

objdescr_s: Wooden model scene of men & women: bread makers (tallest figure is 9 1/4" high); male- miller; male- stacking bread molds; female- sifter; female- sifter.
name: Model of Bread-Making Scene
hint:
Bread was a staple of the ancient Egyptian diet, and grain for making bread was one common form of payment for work.

Because it was so important in this life, bread was an offering to the dead for their afterlife.

objdescr_s: Pottery; smooth, pinkish jar,  flaring mouth, incised line on neck
name: Jar
hint:
Beer, wine, honey, and olive oil were stored in jars and offered to the dead. This jar represents beer, called henket.

The jar has two colors because this type of red clay pottery is fired upside down, to make a decorative black shiny top.

objdescr_s: pottery shabti jar with painted figures; the deceased (woman) kneels before Anubis, in form of a jackal on shrine.  3 of 4 sons of Horus: Hapy, Duamutef and Imseti on other side.
name: Jackal
hint: In Egypt, the death god Anubis was represented by a jackal head; but not every jackal was Anubis. The jackal on this jar does represent the god seated on a shrine.

objdescr_s: Type IV model boat, sailed; 4 sailors, 1 pilot/lookout & 2 helmsmen. Canopy supported by 6 posts with coffin beneath. 1 stearing oar survived (originally 2), gangplank, 2 morring stakes, bailing bucket, 6 oars, part of bipod mast, 3 spars. Boat is white with yellow painted details
name: Model Funerary Boat with Crew
hint: Ancient Egyptians visualized death as a boat journey across the Nile. The funerary boat transported the soul from this life to the afterlife. So models of funerary boats were often included in tombs.

objdescr_s: green faience; Mn-hpr-Rc, flanked by 2 ma'at feathers and 2 ureii.
name: Feathers (on a scarab)
hint:
The feathers on this scarab represent Ma’at, the goddess of truth, justice, and order. Ancient Egyptians feared chaos above all else, so much was done to make Ma’at happy!

The feather is also an important symbol used in the Weighing of the Heart ceremony conducted by Anubis.

objdescr_s: wooden animal leg, painted red, black and white; model of beef haunch.
name: Model Beef Haunch
hint:
Cows were an important part of the ancient Egyptian agricultural system, providing labor, meat, and milk products.

They were also important in religion. In some instances, cows symbolized the very popular goddess Hathor.
